text_fields: Blanket, Index Collection. White blanket with bands of blocks of single colors and mixed colors, increasing in saturation by steps of 10% from one side to the other. This blanket takes the language of the print world—monotone, duotone, and multitoned color blending—and expresses it in weaving. The increasing saturation of the colors is brought about by bringing more warp threads to the surface of the weave structure. . Made of organic cotton warp, merino wool weft. Blanket, 2012. Designed or created by Textile Museum (Woven by). From Netherlands. Credit: Gift of Raw Color.

text_fields: Tapestry, Nightless Night, from the Reveille series. None Saksi utilizes sinuous, psychedelic patterns in a series of tapestries meant to invoke memories of growing up in Kouvola, Finland. His Reveille series experiments with Jacquard weaving techniques. In Nightless Night, moths, bats, and celestial constellations serve to visualize the sleeping mind at the edge of waking up. In addition to traditional materials, Saksi uses rubber, acrylic, lurex, and phosphorescent yarn with mohair and cashmere wool to complete his tapestries.. Made of jacquard-woven mohair and rubber. Tapestry, 2015. Designed or created by Textile Museum (Lent by). From . Credit: Courtesy of Kustaa Saksi.

text_fields: Wig Stand (France). On pierced globe, a continuous landscape that includes figures and a tree, in cobalt blue and manganese purple. Brown overglaze partially scraped off. Tri-foil scroll design on pedestal. . Made of tin-glazed earthenware, underglaze and overglaze decoration. Wig stand, mid-18th century. Designed or created by Richard Cranch Greenleaf (American, 1887–1961) (Bequest of). From France. Credit: Bequest of Richard Cranch Greenleaf in memory of his mother, Adeline Emma Greenleaf.

text_fields: Waistcoat Fronts (France). Left and right fronts of a gentleman's waistcoat with no collar, shaped lower edge and pocket flaps, embroidered in fourteen colors of silk with sequins and paste jewels on an ivory silk ground. Overall tiny floral sprig, floral border at center front, and design of sailing ships and swagged garlands at lower edge. . Made of silk, metal wire, sequins, paste jewels. Waistcoat fronts, ca. 1760. Designed or created by George Saville Seligman (Previously owned by), Richard Cranch Greenleaf (American, 1887–1961) (Bequest of). From France. Credit: Bequest of Richard Cranch Greenleaf in memory of his mother, Adeline Emma Greenleaf.
